"I'm not too worried about myself. I'm just a little bit worried about not doing well enough or holding the team back because of my limited experience. "

2,216 words, about 4 minutes to read

At 3 a.m. on Jan. 30, nurse Wang Hao removed the last leg holster and left the quarantine area of Wuhan Union Hospital, clutching her swollen hand.

On January 27, the Beijing medical team flew to Wuhan to help, and the age difference was significant: from veterans of SARS, H7n9 and other epidemics to young people who had never worn protective clothing. Wang Hao, born in 1995, is the youngest of 26"post-1990" members of the 136-strong medical team, according to statistics. He thinks, can not let the elder stand in the draught only, young strength should stand out.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Beijing aided Wuhan medical team as the youngest player -- Wang Hao. Photo by Tao ran, Beijing News



Out of quarantine, too tired to talk

Beijing News: Yesterday is your first time to enter the quarantine zone to care for the infected?

Wang Hao: that's right. It was the first time I had ever trained in a quarantine suit, but it was the first time I had ever been so tightly wrapped as to enter a quarantine zone to treat an infected COVID-19. The 29th was the first day the ward was open, we got to the hospital at 9:00 pm, got out of the shelter at 9:20,3:10 am on the 30th. I felt like I was in a war zone before I went in, and I was a little worried that I was going to make it.

Beijing News: is the situation in there what you expected?

Wang Hao: a little better than I expected. On the first day, the medical team treated more than a dozen patients, most of whom were not seriously ill. I heard that the experts from Beijing had arrived and they were in a stable mood. Our job is to assist the doctor to carry out treatment and monitor the patient's vital signs, including taking their temperature and blood oxygen, infusion and so on. The work is not imagined in the difficult, but the protection gave the very big pressure, usually walks, hangs the liquid is very simple, but wrapped one layer after another, the simple movement becomes quite difficult.

Beijing News: How do you feel after coming out?

Wang Hao: JUST TIRED! We've been in there for six hours, and it's really hard to wear protection. And I'm a little bit of a loser, I'm too tall, my hands are too big, I wear the biggest isolator, and I have to watch my range of motion, otherwise my head might be exposed, my hands are uncomfortable, I'm wearing three layers of gloves, and my hands are almost purple. I went back to my place for a while, and then I went to sleep.

Beijing News: Two days ago in the hospital to see the Adult diaper, you wear it?

Wang Hao: We couldn't take our clothes off, we couldn't go to the bathroom, we had to wear diapers, even if we didn't want to, but I knew how to do it under the guidance of a colleague who was a dad and had a lot of experience. I didn't think I'd be wearing diapers at 24, but I didn't use them until I got out, and I'm kind of happy about that.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Wang Hao (left) with medical team members

I've been waiting to go to the front, and my mother blames herself for that

Beijing News: Is Coming to Wuhan to support the fight against the epidemic the most exciting thing you've ever done?

Wang Hao: Definitely in my career.

Beijing News: How did this matter settle down?

Wang Hao: it's kind of sudden. At noon on January 26, when I was working in the hospital, the head nurse suddenly sent out a message in the group asking me to report it within two hours, asking nurses to have at least three years of work experience, and I happened to be working for just over three years, let's get the names in the paper. We'll have the list by the end of the day. The next day the time is even more urgent, the group at 1:07 noon notice, let us gather at 2:00, I the day before the night shift, sleep until 1:20, quickly wake up the teammates, each rushed home to get some toiletries and left, the same day flew to Wuhan.

Beijing News: How do you think before you sign up?

Wang Hao: I've been waiting for this opportunity for a long time. News of the outbreak has been coming out every day for some time now. At first, I didn't pay much attention to it, but later I realized it was serious when I confirmed it was passed from one person to another. Wuhan is a very popular city with a large number of people, and in time for the Spring Festival, I always wanted to come here and make a contribution. It's really happening.

Beijing News: You are the youngest team, not long to participate in the work, afraid?

Wang Hao: I'm not really worried about myself. I'm just a little worried about not doing a good job or slowing the team down because of my limited experience. This period of time has been looking at the epidemic related information, catch up on the knowledge. Many teachers in the team experienced, some experienced SARS, a stream, but I feel that the danger can not just let the old-timers in the vent, every era needs young people to make an example. In fact, the young force has come forward, Beijing medical team after 90 many, the hospital's nurses are even smaller, some are 96,97, have come to the front without their families to work overtime, I am particularly touched.

Beijing News: Did you discuss it with your parents before you left?

Wang Hao: it's too late to tell them. Come out of the ward. The sign-up is confirmed. Didn't feel the need to worry them, so I didn't say it.

Beijing News: How did they react?

Wang Hao: My father always felt that when the country was in crisis and he had the ability, he had to go. My mother was very worried. When she found out that I had come to Wuhan, she didn't return my messages for half a day. Then she called me and asked me not to blame her. She cried for a long time after she heard the news, i'm afraid of what it might do to me. My mother was a very strong woman, and I had never seen her like this since I was a child. I feel a little guilty for not only being a nurse, but also a son, for not taking their feelings into consideration.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Wang Hao (first left) , members of the medical team with the patient. Photo courtesy of the respondents

It wasn't until Wuhan that I felt like I was on the battlefield

Beijing News: How did you feel when you arrived in Wuhan?

Wang Hao: Before the departure is a cavity warm blood, after the mood down, rational up, the mood is more complex, after all, the epidemic is still very serious. When the experts teach us to put on our Hazmat suits, the feeling of going to war comes. Fortunately, our hospital this time are boys (nurses) , we talk about this matter, ease the tension.

Beijing News: How did you spend the last few days?

Wang Hao: arrived in the early morning of the 28th, and spent a lot of time training in quarantine protection. Shi Yuexin, Xin Feng and Yuan Lei, teachers of the medical team, have experience. They provide guidance and also warn of possible accidents, for example, shoe covers need extra tape to hold them in place, or they may fall off. Each person's hands are of a different shape. Gloves need to be held in place. Yesterday (the 29th) just began to report safe, reply to some of the family and friends information, told them not to worry, tidy up the room.

I was the 29th night shift at 9:00, the time is a bit awkward, sleep also can not sleep, have been thinking about the things on the line, finally wait for this day, very excited. Number 30 came out and got a good night's sleep.

Beijing News: How long can you accept the support here?

Wang Hao: As long as Hubei Needs, we can watch the 2021 here.

 background:

On January 27, the Wuhan Medical Team from the Beijing Municipal Hospital set out to support the Wuhan Union Hospital.

On Jan. 29, the Beijing medical team began treating pneumonia patients infected with COVID-19 after the quarantine ward was opened.

Beijing medical team has 136 members, according to statistics, including 90 after 26,95 after 4, are all municipal hospitals in Beijing nurses.
